    <text id="R11218118T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>In late April, 1862, Confederate General Thomas J. Jackson positioned his forces
                    to assume the offensive. In this letter, Union General Nathaniel P. Banks
                    reports to Secretary of War Stanton on Jackson's movements, and the location of
                    Johnson's Confederate troops outside Staunton.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">Hon. E.M. STANTON,<lb/> Secretary of War:</name>

                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1862-04-30">April 30, 1862.</date>
                        <name type="place">NEW MARKET,</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute/>
                </opener>
                <p>All quiet. Some alarm excited by movement of enemy's cavalry. It appears to-day
                    that they were in pursuit of Union prisoner who escaped to our camp at Alma
                    Bridge. He reports Jackson at foot of Blue Ridge. Ordnance train sent over
                    mountains. The day he left, Jackson was to be re-enforced by Johnson and to make
                    attack via Luray. Another report says Jackson is bound for Richmond. This is the
                    fact, I have no doubt. Johnson is west of Staunton 6 miles; Milroy in his rear.
                    Jackson is on half rations, his supplies having been cut off by our advance.
                    There is nothing to be done in this valley this side of fortifications this side
                    of Strasburg.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute/>
                    <signed>N.P. BANKS,<lb/> Maj.-Gen., Commanding.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
